We can factor a constant out of the first radical:
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{4+\sqrt{16+16a}} &= \sqrt{4+\sqrt{16(1+a)}}\\
&= \sqrt{4+4\sqrt{1+a}}\\
&= \sqrt{4(1+\sqrt{1+a})}\\
&= 2\sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+a}}
\end{align*}Then, we can combine like terms and solve:

\begin{align*}
2\sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+a}}+ \sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+a}} &= 6\\
\Rightarrow 3\sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+a}} &= 6\\
\Rightarrow \sqrt{1+\sqrt{1+a}} &= 2\\
\Rightarrow 1+\sqrt{1+a} &= 4\\
\Rightarrow \sqrt{1+a} &= 3\\
\Rightarrow 1+a &= 9\\
\Rightarrow a &= \boxed{8}
\end{align*}

There are $\binom{5}{2} = 10$ different pairs of marbles that can be drawn, and the expected value of the product is the average of the products of each pair.  This is  \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{10}[(1\times 2)&+(1\times 3)+(1\times 4)+(1\times 5)+{}\\
&(2\times 3)+(2\times 4)+(2\times 5)+(3\times 4)+(3\times 5)+(4\times 5)]\\
&\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad=\frac{85}{10} = \boxed{8.5}. \end{align*}

